POM XML :
pom.xml stands for Project Object Model XML. It defines the configuration for a Maven project, including:
•	Project metadata (name, version, description)
•	Dependencies (external libraries your project needs)
•	Plugins (tools for compiling, testing, packaging, etc.)

groupId: Unique ID for your project group (like a package name).
artifactId: The name of the project.

1. Spring Boot Starter Web 
Purpose: To build web applications, including RESTful services.
Includes: Spring MVC, Embedded Tomcat (or Jetty/Undertow), Jackson (for JSON serialization/deserialization)
@RestController, request handling and all takes place.

2. Spring Boot Starter Data JPA 
Purpose: To simplify database access using JPA (Java Persistence API) and Hibernate.
Includes: Spring Data JPA, Hibernate (default JPA implementation)
Mapping Java objects to database tables, creating repositories with minimal boilerplate, Performing CRUD operations.
@Entity, @Id, @GeneratedValue

3. Lombok 
Purpose: To reduce boilerplate code in Java classes.
•	Automatically generates getters, setters, constructors, toString(), etc.
•	Improves code readability and maintainability

4. Spring Boot Starter Validation 
Purpose: To validate user input using annotations (JSR-380 / Bean Validation).
•	Hibernate Validator (default implementation)
•	Validating request bodies in REST APIs, Ensuring data integrity before processing



5. Spring Boot Starter Security 
Purpose: To add authentication and authorization to your application.
Includes: Spring Security framework
•	Securing REST endpoints, Role-based access control, Integrating with OAuth2, JWT, LDAP, etc.

6. MySQL JDBC Driver (mysql-connector-j)
Purpose: To connect your Spring Boot application to a MySQL database.
•	Enables JDBC communication between the app and MySQL
•	Required for Spring Data JPA to interact with MySQL


application.properties :
       Src/main/resources/application.properties
application.properties file is a key configuration file that helps to
•	Configure database connections
•	Set server properties
•	Define logging levels
•	Customize Spring Boot behavior
•	Manage security settings
•	Configure third-party integrations

spring.jpa.properties.hibernate.dialect=org.hibernate.dialect.MySQLDialect
Here we are explicitly telling hibernate to use SQL syntax and behavior optimized for MySQL.
A dialect in Hibernate is a class that defines how Hibernate should generate SQL queries for a specific database. Different databases have different SQL syntax, functions, and behaviors. The dialect ensures compatibility between Hibernate and the database.

spring.jpa.hibernate.ddl-auto=update
•	Other options: none, validate, create, create-drop.
